{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b98a5ef768289e83", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t\n2\t===PAGE 1===\n3\tDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\n4\tSummary of DCASE 2026 Task 5: Audio-Dependent Question Answering\n5\tHaolin He, 1,∗ Renhe Sun, 2,∗ Zheqi Dai, 1 Xingjian Du, 3 Chunyat Wu, 1 Zining Liang, 1\n6\tZhengxi Liu, 1 Jiahe Lei, 1 Runbang Wang,1 Jiayi Zhou, 2 Mingru Yang,2 Xiquan Li, 4 Yun Chen,5\n7\tXie Chen, 4 Zhiyao Duan, 3 Weiqiang Wang,2 Mark D. Plumbley, 5 Jian Liu, 2,† Qiuqiang Kong 1,†\n8\t1The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR 2Ant Group, China\n9\t3University of Rochester, USA 4Shanghai Jiao Tong University, China 5King’s College London, UK\n10\tAbstract—DCASE 2026 Task 5 introduces Audio-Dependent Question\n11\tAnswering (ADQA), which tests whether large audio-language models\n12\tanswer from the audio rather than from textual priors. An Audio-\n13\tDependency Filtering (ADF) pipeline combines silent-audio probing, per-\n14\toption perplexity, a large language model (LLM) commonsense check,\n15\tand human review to remove items solvable from text alone. The 3000\n16\titems that pass form the ADQA-Bench evaluation set, spanning music,\n17\tspeech, and environmental audio. The inaugural edition draws 14 teams\n18\tand 36 submissions across two tracks defined by total parameter count\n19\t(up to 100B and under 10B). A Chung-Ang University ensemble of\n20\tMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking and Qwen3-Omni-30B reaches the top overall\n21\taccuracy at 58.33 %, and a MOSS-only configuration from the same\n22\tteam leads the sub-10B track at 57.30 %. Across the 30 submissions\n23\twith a comparable development score, evaluation accuracy falls by 11.91\n24\tpercentage points (pp) on average (median 10.91 pp) on the hidden\n25\tevaluation split, which is designed to be harder than the development split.\n26\tThe most common building blocks are: the MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking\n27\tbackbone (13 of 36 submissions), Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) fine-\n28\ttuning on AudioMCQ-StrongAC, and preference or reinforcement-learning\n29\tobjectives—Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) in five teams,\n30\tGroup reward-Decoupled Normalization Policy Optimization (GDPO) in\n31\ttwo. At test time, prompt engineering is near-universal, and majority or\n32\tchoice-permutation voting is common. Every system misses the same set\n33\tof 233 evaluation items.\n34\tIndex Terms—Audio question answering, large audio-language models,\n35\tmultimodal evaluation, DCASE challenge\n36\t1. INTRODUCTION\n37\tLarge Audio-Language Models (LALMs) can inflate their accuracy\n38\ton multiple-choice audio benchmarks by partly exploiting textual\n39\tshortcuts rather than the audio itself. Replace the audio with silence\n40\tand state-of-the-art LALMs still answer many questions correctly,\n41\tusing linguistic priors and dataset artifacts [1]–[4]. Progress requires\n42\tbenchmarks that remove such items, and models that answer from\n43\tthe audio signal itself.\n44\tDCASE 2026 Task 5, Audio-Dependent Question Answering\n45\t(ADQA) [1], addresses this gap. An Audio-Dependency Filtering\n46\t(ADF) pipeline drops questions that a text-only model can solve,\n47\tleaving a 3000-item evaluation set (ADQA-Bench). Submissions\n48\tare open-source LALMs that answer four-way multiple-choice\n49\tquestions grounded in the audio. Two tracks run in parallel,\n50\tsplit by total parameter count: an Overall track ( ≤100B) and\n51\ta Lightweight track (<10B).\n52\tThe top Overall system, Lim_CAU from Chung-Ang University [5],\n53\treaches 58.33 %; the same team wins the Lightweight track at 57.30 %.\n54\tThe strongest organizer baseline, Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct\n55\t(hereafter Qwen3-Omni-30B) [6], scores 62.48 % on development.\n56\tBaselines are run only on development. Team submissions average\n57\t∼12 pp below their own development scores on the harder hidden\n58\tsplit [1] (Section 5.2), so this baseline number is not directly\n59\t∗Equal contribution. †Corresponding authors.\n60\tThe authors thank the 14 participating teams of DCASE 2026 Task 5 for\n61\ttheir submissions and technical reports.\n62\tHard-ADF\n63\tSoft-ADF\n64\tLLM\n65\tHuman Verification\n66\tAudioMCQ-SAC-GCoT\n67\tTrainEval\n68\tRank\n69\tLALMs\n70\tBenchmarks &Human-annotated Questions\n71\tADQA-Bench\n72\t...\n73\tCompute Accuracy\n74\tFig. 1: The ADF pipeline. Three filtering stages (Hard-ADF, Soft-ADF, large\n75\tlanguage model (LLM) commonsense) and a final human verification step\n76\tyield ADQA-Bench from existing benchmarks and newly annotated multiple-\n77\tchoice-question (MCQ) items; training items follow the related Strong Audio-\n78\tContribution (StrongAC) selection on the AudioMCQ corpus [1], with chain-\n79\tof-thought (CoT) rationales; the figure’s AudioMCQ-SAC-GCoT block denotes\n80\tthis AudioMCQ-StrongAC-GeminiCoT training corpus (SAC = StrongAC;\n81\tGCoT = Gemini-distilled CoT).\n82\tcomparable to the team eval accuracies. Every system beats\n83\tthe random-guess baseline (25.46 %, above 25 % likely due to\n84\toption-length and distractor artifacts). The median across the 36\n85\tsubmissions is 50.87 %, and the top score of 58.33 % leaves\n86\tclear headroom on ADQA-Bench.\n87\tSection 2 details the task and ADF, Section 3 the submissions,\n88\tSection 4 the methods, Section 5 the performance analysis, and\n89\tSection 6 the discussion and future directions.\n90\t2. TASK SETUP AND DATASET\n91\t2.1. Task Definition\n92\tDCASE 2026 Task 5 (ADQA) is a four-way multiple-choice question\n93\t(MCQ) task over audio clips. Each item pairs one audio recording, one\n94\tquestion, and four options with a single correct choice. Every question\n95\tmust beaudio-dependent: the correct answer cannot be recovered\n96\tfrom the text alone.\n97\t2.2. Audio-Dependency Filtering (ADF)\n98\tThe ADF cascade [1] is a four-stage pipeline (Fig. 1) that keeps only\n99\titems whose correct answer depends on the audio signal.\n100\tHard-ADF (silent-audio probe).We replace the audio with silence\n101\tand ask a pool of LALMs to answer. An item is discarded if more\n102\tthan one blind model still picks the correct option, since the answer\n103\tis then largely recoverable without listening.\n104\tSoft-ADF (perplexity filter).We score each option with language-\n105\tmodel perplexity under silent audio. If the correct option has the\n106\tlowest perplexity, the item is dropped: a text-only preference for the\n107\tright answer exposes a linguistic shortcut.\n108\tLLM commonsense filter.A text-only large language model (LLM)\n109\tsees the question and options without the audio. Items it answers\n110\tcorrectly from commonsense or world knowledge are pruned.\n111\tarXiv:2607.18718v1  [eess.AS]  21 Jul 2026\n112\t===PAGE 2===\n113\tDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\n114\tTable 1: Top-1 accuracy of organizer baselines on the development set. Random-\n115\tguess level: 25.46 %.\n116\tBaseline system Accuracy\n117\tFun-Audio-Chat-8B [7] 56.81 %\n118\tKimi-Audio-7B [8] 46.36 %\n119\tMiMo-Audio-7B [9] 54.57 %\n120\tQwen3-Omni-30B [6]62.48 %\n121\tStep-Audio-2 Mini [10] 50.53 %\n122\tRandom guess 25.46 %\n123\tHuman verification.A two-pass human review checks that the\n124\tlabeled answer is correct given the audio and that every distractor is\n125\tplausible but acoustically wrong.\n126\t2.3. Datasets\n127\tTraining set.The official training corpus, AudioMCQ-StrongAC-\n128\tGeminiCoT (hereafter AudioMCQ-StrongAC), is derived from the\n129\t∼571k-item AudioMCQ corpus [1]. We keep a subset of the Strong\n130\tAudio-Contribution (StrongAC) split and add chain-of-thought (CoT)\n131\trationales distilled from Gemini 3.1 Pro.\n132\tDevelopment set.1607 MCQ items drawn from existing bench-\n133\tmarks (MMAU [2], MMAR [3], MMSU [4]) together with newly\n134\tannotated questions, all passing the four-stage ADF.\n135\tEvaluation set.The hidden ADQA-Bench holds 3000 MCQ items\n136\tfiltered under the same protocol. Team-submission scores in this paper\n137\trefer to this evaluation set, whereas organizer baseline numbers refer\n138\tto the development set alone (Section 5.2).\n139\tProtocol.Two tracks are defined by total parameter count: Overall\n140\t(≤100B total, no component >30B ) and Lightweight ( <10B ).\n141\tSubmissions must use open-source LALMs. Manual annotation of\n142\tevaluation items is forbidden: teams cannot label evaluation audio by\n143\thand, re-transcribe it for training, or feed per-item human answers\n144\tback into their systems. Each team can submit up to four systems.\n145\t2.4. Baseline Systems\n146\tThe organizers release five LALM baselines with tuned prompts and\n147\tscore them by top-1 accuracy on the development set. Table 1 reports\n148\tthese scores next to a random-guess level of 25.46 %. This exceeds\n149\t25 % likely because option-length and distractor artifacts make a few\n150\tchoices slightly more likely than a uniform guess. Qwen3-Omni-30B\n151\tscores highest among the baselines.\n152\t3. SUBMISSION OVERVIEW\n153\tThe first edition of DCASE 2026 Task 5 draws 14 teams and 36\n154\tranked submissions, spanning 31.87 % to 58.33 % accuracy. Because\n155\teach system is scored on 3000 items, gaps of about a percentage point\n156\tshould be read as ties. Every system is built on one of six public\n157\tLALMs, so teams differ mainly in their backbone choice and how\n158\tthey curate data around it.\n159\tThe overall champion is Lim_CAU_4 from Chung-Ang Univer-\n160\tsity [5], which reaches 58.33 % by ensembling MOSS-Audio-8B-\n161\tThinking [11] with Qwen3-Omni-30B [6] (96.0 B in the challenge\n162\tmetadata; the team reports a 92 B effective total over four MOSS-\n163\t8B and two Qwen3-Omni-30B inference views). Its pipeline\n164\tchains audio-vs-silent difficulty binning, Group reward-Decoupled\n165\tNormalization Policy Optimization (GDPO) [12]-based Low-Rank\n166\tAdaptation (LoRA) [13], an inference-time acoustic tagger, and\n167\tchoice-permutation ensembling (see Section 4.4). Nam_IND [14]\n168\tapplies 4-bit quantized LoRA (QLoRA) [15] supervised fine-tuning\n169\t(SFT) with a response normalizer on Qwen3-Omni-30B (60 B,\n170\t57.17 %). Hu_IOA [16] runs MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking with zero-\n171\tshot label-only decoding and 5-view choice-permutation majority\n172\t0 20 40 60 80\n173\tEval Accuracy (%)\n174\tLim_CAU\n175\tNam_IND\n176\tHu_IOA\n177\tYin_XJTLU\n178\tCheng_Surrey\n179\tZhang_WHU\n180\tTathe_UIUC\n181\tHuang_JAIST\n182\tKim_SGU\n183\tWu_XMU\n184\tZC_Inst\n185\tGuan_HEU\n186\tSong_BIT\n187\tXu_HUST\n188\t(58.33%)\n189\t(57.17%)\n190\t(57.03%)\n191\t(56.00%)\n192\t(53.93%)\n193\t(51.57%)\n194\t(50.60%)\n195\t(49.60%)\n196\t(49.13%)\n197\t(47.20%)\n198\t(46.03%)\n199\t(43.37%)\n200\t(43.33%)\n201\t(31.87%)\n202\tMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking\n203\tMOSS-Audio-4B-Instruct\n204\tFun-Audio-Chat-8B\n205\tQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct\n206\tQwen2.5-Omni-7B\n207\tMiMo-Audio-7B-Instruct\n208\tFig. 2: Best eval-set accuracy per team, color-coded by primary base LALM.\n209\tThe dashed line marks the 49.65 % mean across the 14 teams’ best submissions;\n210\tfour teams reach at least 56 %.\n211\tvoting (57.03 %). Yin_XJTLU [17] builds a training-free Qwen3-Omni-\n212\t30B prompt-program ensemble (56.00 %). Cheng_Surrey [18] adds\n213\tretrieval augmentation to MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking (53.93 %), and\n214\tZhang_WHU [19] combines SFT with reinforcement learning (RL) on\n215\tthe same backbone (51.57 %). The remaining eight teams [20]–[27]\n216\tspan from 31.87 % to 50.60 %.\n217\tTable 2 lists all 36 ranked submissions, with † marking lightweight-\n218\teligible systems ( <10B ); Fig. 2 plots each team’s best accuracy\n219\tagainst the lightweight bar. The lightweight champion is Lim_CAU_1\n220\tat 57.30 %, 1.03 pp behind the 96 B ensemble.\n221\tMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking is the most common backbone at\n222\tthe top of the leaderboard. Four of 14 teams ( Lim_CAU, Hu_IOA,\n223\tCheng_Surrey, Zhang_WHU) pick it as the backbone of their best\n224\tsubmission, and Yin_XJTLU uses it in three of four submissions.\n225\tInside Hu_IOA, an un-fine-tuned MOSS run reaches 57.03 % while\n226\ttheir tuned Qwen2.5-Omni-7B [16], [28] scores 49.87 %; this pair\n227\tconfounds base model, size, and tuning status, so we treat it as\n228\tone data point. Without controlled ablations we cannot separate\n229\tthe contributions of checkpoint alignment, LoRA [13] compatibility\n230\t(Lim_CAU,Zhang_WHU), and retrieval support (Cheng_Surrey).\n231\tAmong the top five, Yin_XJTLU favors MOSS overall, yet its\n232\tbest submission uses a different backbone. Its Qwen3-Omni prompt-\n233\tprogram ensemble ( Yin_XJTLU_1, 56.00 %) narrowly beats its own\n234\tMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking variants: audio-token attention biases\n235\t(Yin_XJTLU_2/Yin_XJTLU_3) and an option-elimination prompt\n236\tprogram ( Yin_XJTLU_4). Later sections analyze these submissions\n237\tby paradigm, backbone, and common techniques (Section 4), and by\n238\ttheir performance patterns (Section 5).\n239\t4. METHODOLOGIES AND TRENDS\n240\tWe compare the 36 submissions by backbone and technique, and the\n241\t14 teams by training paradigm—one label per team, taken from its\n242\tbest system and applied to all of that team’s submissions. Paradigm\n243\tcomparisons are descriptive only: cell sizes (1–5 teams) are too small\n244\tfor statistical inference, and paradigm is closely confounded with\n245\teach team’s backbone choice.\n246\t4.1. Paradigm Taxonomy\n247\tEach team’s best system falls into one of six paradigms (see Table 2),\n248\treported as best, mean, and team count (best omitted where not\n249\tinformative): hybrid (58.33 %, 54.83 %, 3), training-free (56.00 %,\n250\t===PAGE 3===\n251\tDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\n252\tTable 2: All 36 ranked submissions on the DCASE 2026 Task 5 evaluation set, sorted by Eval accuracy. The overall champion is shown in bold; † marks\n253\tlightweight systems whose total system size is below 10 B parameters. Dev/Eval = development/evaluation-set top-1 accuracy; Diff = Eval − Dev in percentage\n254\tpoints (pp); – marks submissions with no published development score. Paradigm is a team-level label from each team’s best system, shared by all its submissions.\n255\tParadigm abbreviations: H = Hybrid, S = SFT only, S+R = SFT+RL, RL = RL only, TF = Training-free, RAG = Retrieval-augmented generation. Backbone\n256\tabbreviations: MOSS-8B-Think = MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking; Qwen3-Omni-30B = Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct; Qwen3-Emb = Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B;\n257\tMiMo-Audio-7B = MiMo-Audio-7B-Instruct; MOSS-4B-Instruct = MOSS-Audio-4B-Instruct. The 80.0 B figure for Lim_CAU_3 follows the challenge-metadata\n258\treplicated-view convention for a single 8 B MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking checkpoint used across ten permutation views (8 B unique weights); the 96.0 B for\n259\tLim_CAU_4 likewise follows the metadata, while its report states a 92 B effective total over six inference views. o: oracle upper bound for the category-aware\n260\taudio-attention setting reported byYin_XJTLU; the deployed system’s calibrated dev accuracy is not separately reported.\n261\tRank Submission Institution Paradigm Base LALM Params Dev (%) Eval (%) Diff (%)\n262\t1Lim_CAU_4[5]Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think + Qwen3-Omni-30B 96.0 B 70.50 58.33−12.17\n263\t2Lim_CAU_3[5] Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think 80.0 B 70.01 58.10−11.91\n264\t3Lim_CAU_1[5] † Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think 8.0 B 69.63 57.30−12.33\n265\t4Nam_IND_2[14] Independent S Qwen3-Omni-30B 60.0 B – 57.17 –\n266\t5Nam_IND_4[14] Independent S Qwen3-Omni-30B + Gemma-4-E4B-it 94.0 B – 57.13 –\n267\t6Lim_CAU_2[5] † Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think 8.0 B 69.70 57.07−12.63\n268\t7Hu_IOA_4[16] † IOA, CAS H MOSS-8B-Think + Qwen3-Emb 8.6 B