53 43.33−7.20\n295\t34Song_BIT_2[26] † BIT RL MiMo-Audio-7B 7.0 B 48.10 41.53−6.57\n296\t35Song_BIT_3[26] † BIT RL MiMo-Audio-7B 7.0 B 54.20 40.97−13.23\n297\t36Xu_HUST_1[27] † HUST S MOSS-4B-Instruct + DeBERTa-v3 5.4 B 56.69 31.87−24.82\n298\t51.60 %, 2), supervised fine-tuning with reinforcement learning\n299\t(SFT+RL; mean 51.09 %, 2 teams), SFT only (mean 45.61 %, 5\n300\tteams), and RL only and retrieval-augmented (1 team each).Hybrid\n301\tsystems fuse components from different paradigms [5], [16], [22]\n302\tand achieve the highest best accuracy and mean. Strong SFT-only\n303\t(Nam_IND) and training-free ( Yin_XJTLU) systems still land in the\n304\t55 %–57 % band, within 2.4 pp of the top hybrid system.\n305\t4.2. Base Model Choice\n306\tTable 3 groups submissions by primary backbone. Two models\n307\tdominate. MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking [11] (13 submissions, 5 teams)\n308\tgives the best single-submission accuracy (58.33 %, from a system that\n309\talso fuses Qwen3-Omni-30B views) and a backbone mean of 55.49 %.\n310\tQwen3-Omni-30B [6] (5 submissions, 2 teams) has a slightly higher\n311\traw mean (56.59 %), but four of its five submissions come from one\n312\tteam’s SFT variants, so the cross-team mean is not meaningful at 2\n313\tteams. All other backbones plateau below 51 % [20], [21], [23]–[27].\n314\tIn the one available within-team comparison, added system size gives\n315\tonly marginal gains once a strong 8 B backbone is in place: Lim_CAU’s\n316\t96 B ensemble beats its lightweight entry by only 1.03 pp [5]. A single\n317\tcomparison cannot isolate the effect of size.\n318\t4.3. Commonly Used Techniques\n319\tAcross the 36 submissions, most teams share a small pool of techniques\n320\ton a common backbone. Table 4 lists the 16 technique tags used by at\n321\tTable 3: Submissions grouped by primary base LALM (first model\n322\tlisted in each submission’s meta file). Sorted by the best evaluation-\n323\tset accuracy attained with each backbone. Abbreviations: MOSS-8B-\n324\tThink = MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking; Qwen3-Omni-30B = Qwen3-Omni-30B-\n325\tA3B-Instruct; MOSS-4B-Instruct = MOSS-Audio-4B-Instruct; MiMo-Audio-\n326\t7B = MiMo-Audio-7B-Instruct.\n327\tBase Model #Sub. #Teams Best (%) Mean (%)\n328\tMOSS-8B-Think 13 5 58.33 55.49\n329\tQwen3-Omni-30B 5 2 57.17 56.59\n330\tQwen2.5-Omni-7B 7 3 50.60 49.16\n331\tFun-Audio-Chat-8B 3 3 49.60 46.33\n332\tMiMo-Audio-7B 7 2 49.13 45.51\n333\tMOSS-4B-Instruct 1 1 31.87 31.87\n334\tleast two teams. Prompt engineering (11 teams), LoRA [13] (9), SFT\n335\t(9), and CoT prompting (9) are the most common; Group Relative\n336\tPolicy Optimization (GRPO) [29] appears in 5 teams and majority\n337\tvoting in seven teams.\n338\tChoice-permutation ensembling: Lim_CAU [5] fuses MOSS\n339\tand Qwen3-Omni views via weighted log-probs ( λ≈0.46);\n340\tYin_XJTLU [17] votes across five prompt programs; Zhang_WHU [19]\n341\tgains ∼3.8 pp from eight-sample voting atop GRPO [29].RL\n342\tobjectives: five teams train with GRPO [16], [19], [20], [22],\n343\t[26], and Lim_CAU applies GDPO-style reward normalization on\n344\tLoRA adapters [5].Reward engineering: atop RL, Hu_IOA combines\n345\t===PAGE 4===\n346\tDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\n347\tTable 4: Methodology tags adopted by at least two teams (16 tags total). “Top\n348\tteam” is the best-ranked team that uses the tag in any of its submissions, not\n349\tnecessarily in that team’s best-scoring one, and is not a performance attribution\n350\tfor the tag. Abbreviations: LoRA = Low-Rank Adaptation; SFT = supervised\n351\tfine-tuning; GRPO = Group Relative Policy Optimization; GDPO = Group\n352\treward-Decoupled Normalization Policy Optimization.\n353\tTag #T Top team Tag #T Top team\n354\tPrompt Engineering 11Lim_CAUSelf-Consistency 3Yin_XJTLU\n355\tChain-of-Thought 9Hu_IOAV oting Ensemble 3Lim_CAU\n356\tLoRA 9Lim_CAUChoice-Permut. Ens. 3Lim_CAU\n357\tSFT 9Nam_INDReward Model 3Zhang_WHU\n358\tMajority V oting 7Lim_CAUKnowledge Distill. 2Zhang_WHU\n359\tGRPO 5Hu_IOAGDPO 2Lim_CAU\n360\tHard-Example Mining 4Lim_CAULoRA (4-bit) 2Nam_IND\n361\tTest-Time Scaling 4Lim_CAUPrompt Calibration 2Lim_CAU\n362\taccuracy, format, question-type, embedding-similarity, and length-\n363\tregularization rewards, optimized with GDPO [16], while Song_BIT\n364\tadds an attention-anchoring reward that ties deep-layer cross-attention\n365\tto audio key positions [26].Acoustic-feature injection: Lim_CAU’s\n366\trouter [5] matches question keywords to categories—speech, speaker,\n367\tmusic/scene—and runs only the relevant taggers: voice activity\n368\tdetection (V AD), Whisper [30] prosody, pyannote diarization [31],\n369\tECAPA-TDNN [32] speaker verification, and Contrastive Language-\n370\tAudio Pretraining (CLAP) [33] scene matching, injecting the outputs\n371\tas natural-language snippets.SFT on AudioMCQ-StrongAC: the\n372\tdominant training recipe [16], [19]–[21], [25], with targets from\n373\tanswer text to structured or teacher-rewritten CoT rationales.\n374\t4.4. Winning System:Lim_CAU\n375\tThe winning recipe [5] scores each training candidate under matched\n376\t(audio, silent) prompts and bins them into six difficulty classes. From\n377\t167,541 AudioMCQ-StrongAC [1] candidates, 12,800 rows are drawn\n378\twith group-level quotas. A choice-layout calibration oversamples\n379\toption D targets (A/B/C/D =1.0/1.0/1.0/1.3) to counter reported\n380\tpositional bias in MOSS outputs. GDPO [12]-based LoRA [13] then\n381\ttunes the model. At inference, an acoustic tagger injects librosa [34]-\n382\tderived evidence from the taggers above. The final submission\n383\tLim_CAU_4 fuses MOSS and Qwen3-Omni-30B views via weighted\n384\tlog-probs (λ≈0.46) and reaches 58.33 %, the highest accuracy of any\n385\tsingle submission. No ablation isolates the acoustic tagger from the\n386\ttwo-backbone ensemble, so its standalone gain is unknown.\n387\t5. PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS\n388\t5.1. Question-level Difficulty Distribution\n389\tFigure 3 bins the 3000 evaluation questions by the fraction of\n390\tsubmissions that answer correctly. The distribution is bimodal: 567\n391\tquestions (18.9 %) are solved by fewer than 10 % of systems and 638\n392\t(21.3 %) by more than 90 %. 233 items are missed by every ranked\n393\tsystem; 110 are solved by all. For 47.6 % of items, fewer than half of\n394\tthe 36 submissions answer correctly, so shared failures reach well past\n395\tthe 233-item universal-failure set. This points to weaknesses shared\n396\tby the LALM backbones used here; Section 6 revisits their likely\n397\tcauses in detail.\n398\t5.2. Dev-to-Eval Accuracy Drop\n399\tThe evaluation set is designed to be harder than the development\n400\tsplit [1]. Of the 30 submissions with a comparable development score\n401\t(excluding Nam_IND_2/3/4 and Kim_SGU_4, which publish none,\n402\tand Song_BIT_3 and Yin_XJTLU_3, whose reported numbers are\n403\tan MMAU test-mini proxy and an oracle upper bound), every one\n404\tis lower on eval: mean gap −11.91 pp, median −10.91 pp, standard\n405\tdeviation (SD) 5.24 pp, ranging from −6.6 pp to −25.99 pp. Several\n406\t0 20 40 60 80 100\n407\tPer-Question Accuracy Across 36 Systems (%)\n408\t0\n409\t250\n410\t500Number of Questions\n411\t567\n412\t284\n413\t176 224 178 235 229 161\n414\t308\n415\t638\n416\tFig. 3: Per-question accuracy across the 36 submissions, grouped into ten\n417\t10-percentage-point bins. Mass concentrates in the left-most (hardest) and\n418\tright-most (easiest) bins.\n419\tteams contribute multiple submissions sharing a backbone and training\n420\tdata, son=30 is small and we treat the SD descriptively.\n421\tThe two teams with the largest gaps are Kim_SGU at −25.99 pp\n422\t[22] and Xu_HUST at −24.82 pp [27]; both of which tune adapter\n423\tand leaf selection using development-set analysis, consistent with\n424\tdevelopment-set overfitting. The smallest gaps come from training-free\n425\tor RL-heavy systems whose fine-tuning data excludes development-\n426\tbenchmark items: Song_BIT at −6.6 pp/−7.2 pp [26], Wu_XMU at\n427\t−6.7 pp [23], and Tathe_UIUC at −7.2 pp to −7.83 pp [20], all with\n428\tlower development scores.\n429\t5.3. Reasoning-Time Interventions\n430\tCoT-target SFT raises development accuracy for some systems—\n431\tHu_IOA’s Qwen2.5-Omni from 55.88 % to 57.93 % [16] and\n432\tZhang_WHU’s MOSS-Audio from 52.21 % to 56.94 % [19]—but three\n433\tother reasoning-time add-ons do not. A separate training-time case\n434\tshows the reverse risk: Hu_IOA reports a −8.71 pp development-split\n435\tdrop from SFT on MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking, with development\n436\taccuracy falling from 67.70 % to 58.99 %; they attribute the drop to\n437\tcatastrophic forgetting of the model’s native audio reasoning rather\n438\tthan to CoT supervision itself [16]. Nam_IND loses −1.93 pp with\n439\ta CoT-then-letter prompt [14]. Tathe_UIUC’s Prometheus [35] CoT\n440\tjudge is statistically tied with its no-judge run (57.31 % vs 58.43 %,\n441\tMcNemar p=0.23) [20]. Yin_XJTLU drops −8.96 pp by replacing\n442\tmajority voting with a rule that picks the lowest-entropy branch across\n443\tits training-free prompt programs [17]. This is a decoding-time change\n444\tonly, so it isolates the selection rule from CoT training.\n445\t6. DISCUSSION AND FUTURE DIRECTIONS\n446\tADQA-Bench makes audio dependence measurable: submissions span\n447\t31.87 %–58.33 % on the evaluation set, and 233 items (7.8 %) are\n448\tmissed by every system (Section 5.1). An oracle picking the best\n449\tanswer across the 36 submissions solves 2767 of 3000 items (92.2 %),\n450\tyet no single system comes close. Fine-tuning on AudioMCQ-\n451\tStrongAC derivatives [1], [16], [19], [20] is the most common training\n452\tapproach; Section 5.3 shows reasoning-time interventions give mixed\n453\tresults—CoT-target SFT helps on some backbones, whereas CoT\n454\tprompting, CoT-based judging, and entropy-based branch selection\n455\tdo not. Better acoustic grounding (cf. Section 4) is a next direction,\n456\tthough no submission isolates its contribution [5], [26].\n457\tThe dev-to-eval variance (Section 5.2) motivates a held-out tuning\n458\tsplit, separate from the development set. Because the development set\n459\tre-filters MMAU [2], MMAR [3] and MMSU [4] items (Section 2),\n460\tsuch a split separates benchmark overlap from overfitting. The\n461\t233 universally failed items (Section 5.1) expose capability gaps\n462\tcommon to these LALM backbones, pointing to better audio encoders\n463\tand audio-grounded pre-training. The narrow 1.03 pp gap between\n464\tthe 96 B champion and the 8 B lightweight winner shows data\n465\tcuration and inference-time orchestration rival raw scale. Extending\n466\tthe benchmark to open-ended generation would blunt elimination\n467\tshortcuts but needs an audio-blind judge.\n468\t===PAGE 5===\n469\tDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\n470\tREFERENCES\n471\t[1] H. He, X. Du, R. Sun, Z. Dai, Y . Xiao, M. Yang, J. Zhou, X. Li, Z. Liu,\n472\tZ. Liang, C. Wu, Q. He, T. Lee, X. Chen, W.-L. Zheng, W. Wang,\n473\tM. D. Plumbley, J. Liu, and Q. Kong, “Measuring audio’s impact\n474\ton correctness: Audio-contribution-aware post-training of large audio\n475\tlanguage models,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2509.21060, 2025. [Online].\n476\tAvailable: https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.21060\n477\t[2] S. Sakshi, U. Tyagi, S. Kumar, A. Seth, R. Selvakumar, O. Nieto,\n478\tR. Duraiswami, S. Ghosh, and D. Manocha, “MMAU: A massive\n479\tmulti-task audio understanding and reasoning benchmark,” inProc.\n480\tInt. Conf. Learn. Represent. (ICLR), 2025. [Online]. Available:\n481\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2410.19168\n482\t[3] Z. Ma, Y . Ma, Y . Zhu, C. Yang, Y .-W. Chao, R. Xu, W. Chen,\n483\tY . Chen, Z. Chen, J. Cong, K. Li, K. Li, S. Li, X. Li, X. Li,\n484\tZ. Lian, Y . Liang, M. Liu, Z. Niu, T. Wang, Y . W