or multi-reward RL optimization,” arXiv preprint\n518\tarXiv:2601.05242, 2026. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.\n519\t05242\n520\t[13] E. J. Hu, Y . Shen, P. Wallis, Z. Allen-Zhu, Y . Li, S. Wang, L. Wang,\n521\tand W. Chen, “LoRA: Low-rank adaptation of large language models,”\n522\tinProc. Int. Conf. Learn. Represent. (ICLR), 2022. [Online]. Available:\n523\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2106.09685\n524\t[14] H. Nam, “Learning from audio-dependency errors: Data curation\n525\tstrategies based on model confusion patterns in audio question answering,”\n526\tIndependent, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n527\t[15] T. Dettmers, A. Pagnoni, A. Holtzman, and L. Zettlemoyer, “QLoRA:\n528\tEfficient finetuning of quantized LLMs,” inProc. NeurIPS, 2023.\n529\t[Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.14314\n530\t[16] W. Hu, Y . Cao, and J. Yang, “Audio-dependent question answering at\n531\tthe DCASE 2026 challenge,” Inst. of Acoustics, CAS, DCASE2026\n532\tChallenge, Jun. 2026.\n533\t[17] Z. Yin, Q. Cao, P. Deng, Y . Tan, and S. Li, “Training-free inference-\n534\ttime exploration for audio-dependent question answering,” XJTLU,\n535\tDCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n536\t[18] Y . Cheng, J. Zhao, R. Wan, P. Chang, Y . Chen, and W. Wang, “Selective\n537\tmulti-modal RAG for DCASE 2026 task 5: Audio-dependent question\n538\tanswering,” Univ. of Surrey, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n539\t[19] Y . Zhang, J. Liu, and M. Li, “Structured audio reasoning and robust multi-\n540\tsample inference for DCASE 2026 audio-dependent question answering\n541\tchallenge,” Wuhan Univ. and CUHK-Shenzhen, DCASE2026 Challenge,\n542\tJun. 2026.\n543\t[20] A. Tathe, “DCASE 2026 audio-dependent question answering task,” UIUC\n544\tand CMU, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n545\t[21] Q. Huang, Y . Pan, X. Zhou, R. Li, and M. Unoki, “Curriculum learning\n546\tfor audio-dependent question answering: Technical report for DCASE\n547\t2026 task 5,” JAIST, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n548\t[22] J. Kim, L. Song, and H.-M. Park, “Task-leaf routed MiMo-Audio for\n549\tDCASE 2026 task 5,” Sogang Univ., DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n550\t[23] C. Wu, D. Wu, and Y . Huang, “Qwen2.5-Omni with all-audio audio-TAH\n551\tfor audio-dependent question answering,” Xiamen Univ. and Tsinghua\n552\tUniv., DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n553\t[24] C. Zheng, “Fun-Audio-Chat-8B with LoRA fine-tuning for audio-\n554\tdependent question answering,” Hangzhou Dianzi Univ., DCASE2026\n555\tChallenge, Jun. 2026.\n556\t[25] F. Xiao, Q. Zhu, and J. Guan, “GISP@HEU’s submission for DCASE\n557\t2026 task 5: A LoRA-SFT fine-tuned audio-dependent question answering\n558\tsystem,” HEU and UTS, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n559\t[26] H. Song, “Audio-dependent question answering with attention-anchored\n560\treinforcement learning on MiMo-Audio,” BIT, DCASE2026 Challenge,\n561\tJun. 2026.\n562\t[27] H. Xu and R. Zhang, “Audio question answering at the DCASE 2026\n563\tchallenge,” HUST, DCASE2026 Challenge, Jun. 2026.\n564\t[28] J. Xuet al., “Qwen2.5-Omni technical report,” arXiv preprint\n565\tarXiv:2503.20215, 2025. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2503.\n566\t20215\n567\t[29] Z. Shao, P. Wang, Q. Zhu, R. Xu, J. Song, X. Bi, H. Zhang,\n568\tM. Zhang, Y . K. Li, Y . Wu, and D. Guo, “DeepSeekMath:\n569\tPushing the limits of mathematical reasoning in open language\n570\tmodels,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2402.03300, 2024. [Online]. Available:\n571\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2402.03300\n572\t[30] A. Radford, J. W. Kim, T. Xu, G. Brockman, C. McLeavey,\n573\tand I. Sutskever, “Robust speech recognition via large-scale\n574\tweak supervision,” inProc. ICML, 2023. [Online]. Available:\n575\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2212.04356\n576\t[31] H. Bredin, “pyannote.audio 2.1 speaker diarization pipeline: principle,\n577\tbenchmark, and recipe,” inProc. Interspeech, 2023.\n578\t[32] B. Desplanques, J. Thienpondt, and K. Demuynck, “ECAPA-TDNN:\n579\tEmphasized channel attention, propagation and aggregation in TDNN\n580\tbased speaker verification,” inProc. Interspeech, 2020. [Online].\n581\tAvailable: https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.07143\n582\t[33] Y . Wu, K. Chen, T. Zhang, Y . Hui, M. Nezhurina, T. Berg-Kirkpatrick,\n583\tand S. Dubnov, “Large-scale Contrastive Language-Audio Pretraining\n584\twith feature fusion and keyword-to-caption augmentation,” inProc.\n585\tICASSP, 2023. [Online]. Available: https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.06687\n586\t[34] B. McFee, C. Raffel, D. Liang, D. P. W. Ellis, M. McVicar, E. Battenberg,\n587\tand O. Nieto, “librosa: Audio and music signal analysis in Python,” in\n588\tProc. SciPy, 2015.\n589\t[35] S. Kim, J. Suk, S. Longpre, B. Y . Lin, J. Shin, S. Welleck,\n590\tG. Neubig, M. Lee, K. Lee, and M. Seo, “Prometheus 2: An\n591\topen source language model specialized in evaluating other language\n592\tmodels,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2405.01535, 2024. [Online]. Available:\n593\thttps://arxiv.org/abs/2405.01535\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "959abd70-fd51-427e-905b-e465a2641b27", "uuid": "29c7043a-eda9-46f9-bc4a-21fd6a52b7a7", "timestamp": "2026-07-22T07:04:35.415Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_2607_18718.txt", "content": "\n===PAGE 1===\nDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\nSummary of DCASE 2026 Task 5: Audio-Dependent Question Answering\nHaolin He, 1,∗ Renhe Sun, 2,∗ Zheqi Dai, 1 Xingjian Du, 3 Chunyat Wu, 1 Zining Liang, 1\nZhengxi Liu, 1 Jiahe Lei, 1 Runbang Wang,1 Jiayi Zhou, 2 Mingru Yang,2 Xiquan Li, 4 Yun Chen,5\nXie Chen, 4 Zhiyao Duan, 3 Weiqiang Wang,2 Mark D. Plumbley, 5 Jian Liu, 2,† Qiuqiang Kong 1,†\n1The Chinese University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong SAR 2Ant Group, China\n3University of Rochester, USA 4Shanghai Jiao Tong University, China 5King’s College London, UK\nAbstract—DCASE 2026 Task 5 introduces Audio-Dependent Question\nAnswering (ADQA), which tests whether large audio-language models\nanswer from the audio rather than from textual priors. An Audio-\nDependency Filtering (ADF) pipeline combines silent-audio probing, per-\noption perplexity, a large language model (LLM) commonsense check,\nand human review to remove items solvable from text alone. The 3000\nitems that pass form the ADQA-Bench evaluation set, spanning music,\nspeech, and environmental audio. The inaugural edition draws 14 teams\nand 36 submissions across two tracks defined by total parameter count\n(up to 100B and under 10B). A Chung-Ang University ensemble of\nMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking and Qwen3-Omni-30B reaches the top overall\naccuracy at 58.33 %, and a MOSS-only configuration from the same\nteam leads the sub-10B track at 57.30 %. Across the 30 submissions\nwith a comparable development score, evaluation accuracy falls by 11.91\npercentage points (pp) on average (median 10.91 pp) on the hidden\nevaluation split, which is designed to be harder than the development split.\nThe most common building blocks are: the MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking\nbackbone (13 of 36 submissions), Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) fine-\ntuning on AudioMCQ-StrongAC, and preference or reinforcement-learning\nobjectives—Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) in five teams,\nGroup reward-Decoupled Normalization Policy Optimization (GDPO) in\ntwo. At test time, prompt engineering is near-universal, and majority or\nchoice-permutation voting is common. Every system misses the same set\nof 233 evaluation items.\nIndex Terms—Audio question answering, large audio-language models,\nmultimodal evaluation, DCASE challenge\n1. INTRODUCTION\nLarge Audio-Language Models (LALMs) can inflate their accuracy\non multiple-choice audio benchmarks by partly exploiting textual\nshortcuts rather than the audio itself. Replace the audio with silence\nand state-of-the-art LALMs still answer many questions correctly,\nusing linguistic priors and dataset artifacts [1]–[4]. Progress requires\nbenchmarks that remove such items, and models that answer from\nthe audio signal itself.\nDCASE 2026 Task 5, Audio-Dependent Question Answering\n(ADQA) [1], addresses this gap. An Audio-Dependency Filtering\n(ADF) pipeline drops questions that a text-only model can solve,\nleaving a 3000-item evaluation set (ADQA-Bench). Submissions\nare open-source LALMs that answer four-way multiple-choice\nquestions grounded in the audio. Two tracks run in parallel,\nsplit by total parameter count: an Overall track ( ≤100B) and\na Lightweight track (<10B).\nThe top Overall system, Lim_CAU from Chung-Ang University [5],\nreaches 58.33 %; the same team wins the Lightweight track at 57.30 %.\nThe strongest organizer baseline, Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct\n(hereafter Qwen3-Omni-30B) [6], scores 62.48 % on development.\nBaselines are run only on development. Team submissions average\n∼12 pp below their own development scores on the harder hidden\nsplit [1] (Section 5.2), so this baseline number is not directly\n∗Equal contribution. †Corresponding authors.\nThe authors thank the 14 participating teams of DCASE 2026 Task 5 for\ntheir submissions and technical reports.\nHard-ADF\nSoft-ADF\nLLM\nHuman Verification\nAudioMCQ-SAC-GCoT\nTrainEval\nRank\nLALMs\nBenchmarks &Human-annotated Questions\nADQA-Bench\n...\nCompute Accuracy\nFig. 1: The ADF pipeline. Three filtering stages (Hard-ADF, Soft-ADF, large\nlanguage model (LLM) commonsense) and a final human verification step\nyield ADQA-Bench from existing benchmarks and newly annotated multiple-\nchoice-question (MCQ) items; training items follow the related Strong Audio-\nContribution (StrongAC) selection on the AudioMCQ corpus [1], with chain-\nof-thought (CoT) rationales; the figure’s AudioMCQ-SAC-GCoT block denotes\nthis AudioMCQ-StrongAC-GeminiCoT training corpus (SAC = StrongAC;\nGCoT = Gemini-distilled CoT).\ncomparable to the team eval accuracies. Every system beats\nthe random-guess baseline (25.46 %, above 25 % likely due to\noption-length and distractor artifacts). The median across the 36\nsubmissions is 50.87 %, and the top score of 58.33 % leaves\nclear headroom on ADQA-Bench.\nSection 2 details the task and ADF, Section 3 the submissions,\nSection 4 the methods, Section 5 the performance analysis, and\nSection 6 the discussion and future directions.\n2. TASK SETUP AND DATASET\n2.1. Task Definition\nDCASE 2026 Task 5 (ADQA) is a four-way multiple-choice question\n(MCQ) task over audio clips. Each item pairs one audio recording, one\nquestion, and four options with a single correct choice. Every question\nmust beaudio-dependent: the correct answer cannot be recovered\nfrom the text alone.\n2.2. Audio-Dependency Filtering (ADF)\nThe ADF cascade [1] is a four-stage pipeline (Fig. 1) that keeps only\nitems whose correct answer depends on the audio signal.\nHard-ADF (silent-audio probe).We replace the audio with silence\nand ask a pool of LALMs to answer. An item is discarded if more\nthan one blind model still picks the correct option, since the answer\nis then largely recoverable without listening.\nSoft-ADF (perplexity filter).We score each option with language-\nmodel perplexity under silent audio. If the correct option has the\nlowest perplexity, the item is dropped: a text-only preference for the\nright answer exposes a linguistic shortcut.\nLLM commonsense filter.A text-only large language model (LLM)\nsees the question and options without the audio. Items it answers\ncorrectly from commonsense or world knowledge are pruned.\narXiv:2607.18718v1  [eess.AS]  21 Jul 2026\n===PAGE 2===\nDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\nTable 1: Top-1 accuracy of organizer baselines on the development set. Random-\nguess level: 25.46 %.\nBaseline system Accuracy\nFun-Audio-Chat-8B [7] 56.81 %\nKimi-Audio-7B [8] 46.36 %\nMiMo-Audio-7B [9] 54.57 %\nQwen3-Omni-30B [6]62.48 %\nStep-Audio-2 Mini [10] 50.53 %\nRandom guess 25.46 %\nHuman verification.A two-pass human review checks that the\nlabeled answer is correct given the audio and that every distractor is\nplausible but acoustically wrong.\n2.3. Datasets\nTraining set.The official training corpus, AudioMCQ-StrongAC-\nGeminiCoT (hereafter AudioMCQ-StrongAC), is derived from the\n∼571k-item AudioMCQ corpus [1]. We keep a subset of the Strong\nAudio-Contribution (StrongAC) split and add chain-of-thought (CoT)\nrationales distilled from Gemini 3.1 Pro.\nDevelopment set.1607 MCQ items drawn from existing bench-\nmarks (MMAU [2], MMAR [3], MMSU [4]) together with newly\nannotated questions, all passing the four-stage ADF.\nEvaluation set.The hidden ADQA-Bench holds 3000 MCQ items\nfiltered under the same protocol. Team-submission scores in this paper\nrefer to this evaluation set, whereas organizer baseline numbers refer\nto the development set alone (Section 5.2).\nProtocol.Two tracks are defined by total parameter count: Overall\n(≤100B total, no component >30B ) and Lightweight ( <10B ).\nSubmissions must use open-source LALMs. Manual annotation of\nevaluation items is forbidden: teams cannot label evaluation audio by\nhand, re-transcribe it for training, or feed per-item human answers\nback into their systems. Each team can submit up to four systems.\n2.4. Baseline Systems\nThe organizers release five LALM baselines with tuned prompts and\nscore them by top-1 accuracy on the development set. Table 1 reports\nthese scores next to a random-guess level of 25.46 %. This exceeds\n25 % likely because option-length and distractor artifacts make a few\nchoices slightly more likely than a uniform guess. Qwen3-Omni-30B\nscores highest among the baselines.\n3. SUBMISSION OVERVIEW\nThe first edition of DCASE 2026 Task 5 draws 14 teams and 36\nranked submissions, spanning 31.87 % to 58.33 % accuracy. Because\neach system is scored on 3000 items, gaps of about a percentage point\nshould be read as ties. Every system is built on one of six public\nLALMs, so teams differ mainly in their backbone choice and how\nthey curate data around it.\nThe overall champion is Lim_CAU_4 from Chung-Ang Univer-\nsity [5], which reaches 58.33 % by ensembling MOSS-Audio-8B-\nThinking [11] with Qwen3-Omni-30B [6] (96.0 B in the challenge\nmetadata; the team reports a 92 B effective total over four MOSS-\n8B and two Qwen3-Omni-30B inference views). Its pipeline\nchains audio-vs-silent difficulty binning, Group reward-Decoupled\nNormalization Policy Optimization (GDPO) [12]-based Low-Rank\nAdaptation (LoRA) [13], an inference-time acoustic tagger, and\nchoice-permutation ensembling (see Section 4.4). Nam_IND [14]\napplies 4-bit quantized LoRA (QLoRA) [15] supervised fine-tuning\n(SFT) with a response normalizer on Qwen3-Omni-30B (60 B,\n57.17 %). Hu_IOA [16] runs MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking with zero-\nshot label-only decoding and 5-view choice-permutation majority\n0 20 40 60 80\nEval Accuracy (%)\nLim_CAU\nNam_IND\nHu_IOA\nYin_XJTLU\nCheng_Surrey\nZhang_WHU\nTathe_UIUC\nHuang_JAIST\nKim_SGU\nWu_XMU\nZC_Inst\nGuan_HEU\nSong_BIT\nXu_HUST\n(58.33%)\n(57.17%)\n(57.03%)\n(56.00%)\n(53.93%)\n(51.57%)\n(50.60%)\n(49.60%)\n(49.13%)\n(47.20%)\n(46.03%)\n(43.37%)\n(43.33%)\n(31.87%)\nMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking\nMOSS-Audio-4B-Instruct\nFun-Audio-Chat-8B\nQwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct\nQwen2.5-Omni-7B\nMiMo-Audio-7B-Instruct\nFig. 2: Best eval-set accuracy per team, color-coded by primary base LALM.\nThe dashed line marks the 49.65 % mean across the 14 teams’ best submissions;\nfour teams reach at least 56 %.\nvoting (57.03 %). Yin_XJTLU [17] builds a training-free Qwen3-Omni-\n30B prompt-program ensemble (56.00 %). Cheng_Surrey [18] adds\nretrieval augmentation to MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking (53.93 %), and\nZhang_WHU [19] combines SFT with reinforcement learning (RL) on\nthe same backbone (51.57 %). The remaining eight teams [20]–[27]\nspan from 31.87 % to 50.60 %.\nTable 2 lists all 36 ranked submissions, with † marking lightweight-\neligible systems ( <10B ); Fig. 2 plots each team’s best accuracy\nagainst the lightweight bar. The lightweight champion is Lim_CAU_1\nat 57.30 %, 1.03 pp behind the 96 B ensemble.\nMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking is the most common backbone at\nthe top of the leaderboard. Four of 14 teams ( Lim_CAU, Hu_IOA,\nCheng_Surrey, Zhang_WHU) pick it as the backbone of their best\nsubmission, and Yin_XJTLU uses it in three of four submissions.\nInside Hu_IOA, an un-fine-tuned MOSS run reaches 57.03 % while\ntheir tuned Qwen2.5-Omni-7B [16], [28] scores 49.87 %; this pair\nconfounds base model, size, and tuning status, so we treat it as\none data point. Without controlled ablations we cannot separate\nthe contributions of checkpoint alignment, LoRA [13] compatibility\n(Lim_CAU,Zhang_WHU), and retrieval support (Cheng_Surrey).\nAmong the top five, Yin_XJTLU favors MOSS overall, yet its\nbest submission uses a different backbone. Its Qwen3-Omni prompt-\nprogram ensemble ( Yin_XJTLU_1, 56.00 %) narrowly beats its own\nMOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking variants: audio-token attention biases\n(Yin_XJTLU_2/Yin_XJTLU_3) and an option-elimination prompt\nprogram ( Yin_XJTLU_4). Later sections analyze these submissions\nby paradigm, backbone, and common techniques (Section 4), and by\ntheir performance patterns (Section 5).\n4. METHODOLOGIES AND TRENDS\nWe compare the 36 submissions by backbone and technique, and the\n14 teams by training paradigm—one label per team, taken from its\nbest system and applied to all of that team’s submissions. Paradigm\ncomparisons are descriptive only: cell sizes (1–5 teams) are too small\nfor statistical inference, and paradigm is closely confounded with\neach team’s backbone choice.\n4.1. Paradigm Taxonomy\nEach team’s best system falls into one of six paradigms (see Table 2),\nreported as best, mean, and team count (best omitted where not\ninformative): hybrid (58.33 %, 54.83 %, 3), training-free (56.00 %,\n===PAGE 3===\nDetection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events 2026 28–29 October 2026, Boston, MA, USA\nTable 2: All 36 ranked submissions on the DCASE 2026 Task 5 evaluation set, sorted by Eval accuracy. The overall champion is shown in bold; † marks\nlightweight systems whose total system size is below 10 B parameters. Dev/Eval = development/evaluation-set top-1 accuracy; Diff = Eval − Dev in percentage\npoints (pp); – marks submissions with no published development score. Paradigm is a team-level label from each team’s best system, shared by all its submissions.\nParadigm abbreviations: H = Hybrid, S = SFT only, S+R = SFT+RL, RL = RL only, TF = Training-free, RAG = Retrieval-augmented generation. Backbone\nabbreviations: MOSS-8B-Think = MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking; Qwen3-Omni-30B = Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct; Qwen3-Emb = Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B;\nMiMo-Audio-7B = MiMo-Audio-7B-Instruct; MOSS-4B-Instruct = MOSS-Audio-4B-Instruct. The 80.0 B figure for Lim_CAU_3 follows the challenge-metadata\nreplicated-view convention for a single 8 B MOSS-Audio-8B-Thinking checkpoint used across ten permutation views (8 B unique weights); the 96.0 B for\nLim_CAU_4 likewise follows the metadata, while its report states a 92 B effective total over six inference views. o: oracle upper bound for the category-aware\naudio-attention setting reported byYin_XJTLU; the deployed system’s calibrated dev accuracy is not separately reported.\nRank Submission Institution Paradigm Base LALM Params Dev (%) Eval (%) Diff (%)\n1Lim_CAU_4[5]Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think + Qwen3-Omni-30B 96.0 B 70.50 58.33−12.17\n2Lim_CAU_3[5] Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think 80.0 B 70.01 58.10−11.91\n3Lim_CAU_1[5] † Chung-Ang U. H MOSS-8B-Think 8.0 B 69.63 57.30−12.33\n4Nam_IND_2[14] Independent S Qwen3-Omni-30B 60.0 B – 57.17 –\n5Nam_I